00:24:00,296 --> 00:24:02,679
And eventually he goes to his old five companions.

187
00:24:03,219 --> 00:24:11,769
And the one interesting thing when he meets his companions and he talks to them about this new understanding is that he has this little phrase keeps coming up with, have you ever heard me speak like this before?

188
00:24:13,192 --> 00:24:14,673
Have you ever heard me speak like this before?

189
00:24:15,275 --> 00:24:20,500
And slowly but surely he gains that confidence in passing on his message.

190
00:24:21,162 --> 00:24:22,624
So it's the same with us.

191
00:24:23,431 --> 00:24:31,044
The more we meditate, the more the purification, the more the insight, it comes out just in our very actions, just in the very way that we are.

192
00:24:31,484 --> 00:24:33,327
Whether we like it or not, we become teachers.

193
00:24:34,269 --> 00:24:35,992
We become exemplars.

194
00:24:36,012 --> 00:24:41,863
You should be very ashamed if you get drunk.

195
00:24:41,883 --> 00:24:43,566
You should put yourself in jail for three days.

196
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:56,413
So, you see, if you say, well, I meditate, and then they find you on the street, you know, all palatic, they think, well, what's the point?

197
00:24:56,433 --> 00:25:02,083
So, in a sense, also, we have to bear the burden of our responsibility.

198
00:25:05,587 --> 00:25:12,137
Now, just to explain, I don't have any more time.

199
00:25:13,079 --> 00:25:14,582
So, now, just to explain,

200
00:25:14,848 --> 00:25:17,834
try to understand this process of rebirth.

201
00:25:17,854 --> 00:25:20,257
So the process of rebirth is happening right here and now.

202
00:25:20,657 --> 00:25:26,125
Once we understand that, then the idea of it may be happening after death becomes at least more acceptable.

203
00:25:26,906 --> 00:25:36,101
It's not necessary to believe in any of this in order to become fully liberated for the actual Dharma to work, because the teaching is immediate.

204
00:25:36,161 --> 00:25:38,124
It either works now or it doesn't work.

205
00:25:38,345 --> 00:25:40,468
It's not something that you're preparing for the future.

206
00:25:40,938 --> 00:25:44,863
Meditation either works now, the practice works now, or it doesn't work at all.

207
00:25:47,086 --> 00:25:56,778
Now, if we go back to an original position that the Buddha states of our conditioning, it's this not knowing.

208
00:25:56,798 --> 00:26:06,049
It's a word that begins the process of dependent origination, which is describing the person in flow, in action.

209
00:26:08,092 --> 00:26:10,134
And there's not enough time to go into that

210
00:26:10,553 --> 00:26:15,297
too deeply, but this business of not knowing, what is it that doesn't know?

211
00:26:15,336 --> 00:26:39,919
so it is this satipaṋña, it doesn't know and it arrives in this form at birth, it arrives there in this form so it's no wonder that it should then presume itself to be what it is experiencing so that immediate identity with the physical form

212
00:26:40,220 --> 00:26:51,834
is natural to that consciousness, for want of a better word, to that satipanya, I don't like to use the word consciousness, to the awareness, to that intuitive awareness, that's better.

213
00:26:51,933 --> 00:26:53,336
Or better still, the knowing.

214
00:26:53,935 --> 00:26:55,718
You'll find that in the literature too.

215
00:26:56,118 --> 00:27:05,609
And that's a very clever way of talking about it, because being a sort of verbal form, it gives the impression of it not being stuck substantial, a thing.

216
00:27:06,230 --> 00:27:08,032
It's a process, a knowing, you see.

217
00:27:08,417 --> 00:27:16,826
So this knowing finds itself within this physical frame at a birth point and just presumes this is what I am.

218
00:27:18,107 --> 00:27:21,672
Now as soon as it's done that, it's seeking happiness within this form.

219
00:27:22,452 --> 00:27:27,758
And in seeking happiness within this form, it creates two attitudes.

220
00:27:28,058 --> 00:27:33,104
The first attitude is acquisitiveness, because the more you can have of a good thing, the happier you are.

221
00:27:33,124 --> 00:27:33,243
Right?

222
00:27:33,577 --> 00:28:03,298
and the other one is the opposite anybody who gets in the way must be hated and destroyed annihilated must be completely get out of the way so you've got your you've got your division immediately upon that upon that wrong identity one of acquisition which leads to greed and robbing and all that sort of stuff and one which is getting rid of what is getting in the way which leads to murder and if it's too big it leads the other way see to fear despair suicide so either

223
00:28:03,785 --> 00:28:07,849
it immediately leads us into a position of conflict with the world.

224
00:28:08,651 --> 00:28:26,173
But because, generally speaking, most people find a sort of modicum of living, which is, so we say, at least fairly comfortable, I think I'm only talking about Westerners, that we presume this is the way it should be, this is the way it is.

225
00:28:26,614 --> 00:28:28,797
So Freud, if you remember, came to the conclusion that

226
00:28:29,484 --> 00:28:53,738
there's no way you can get rid of unhappiness you just get to this point where you're not utterly completely neurotic and you sort of have a general feeling of well-being so this that not knowing you see and because it's an original not knowing because it's an original state of

227
00:28:54,393 --> 00:29:02,701
Not knowing, you'll see it translated as ignorance, which gives it the feel of culpability, you know, you should have known better.

228
00:29:03,383 --> 00:29:05,971
But it's not, it's just simply don't know, see.

229
00:29:06,734 --> 00:29:08,942
It's like when we have a real accident, see.

